What you definitely signed up to be reminded about, however, is new music and the Monthly Mix for October 2018 has got you covered. It's got new tracks by Anderson Paak, Courtney Barnett, Toro y Moi and more.

March 2018.title: March 2018
March 2018.description:
Being a Brit who has moved to New York, I massively appreciate the music scene here. London definitely had its fair share of venues but it definitely lacked the DIY attitude that makes New York what it is. It’s safe to say that a lot of artists featured on these playlists got their start on those type of stages.

Which is why it’s such a shame to see the City treat its independent venues like crap. Venues are constantly under threat. Market Hotel has only just re-opened but is being limited to serving beer tasting in a back room because of liquor license rules. Silent Barn, a community art space, and is almost definitely shutting down at the end of the month – almost. There are countless other examples that I won’t bore you with. The truth is most cities would kill for a nightlife scene like New York but instead New York is killing it.

Ok I’ve calmed down now. Here’s some new music! The Monthly Mix for March 2018 is here. It’s got new tracks by New York artists Parquet Courts, Bishop Nehru and Run The Jewels (and about 15 non-NYC artists for balance)

February 2018.title: February 2018
February 2018.description:
This past month I've read a lot of rightly deserved criticism of the Grammys. Most of it about how SZA was unfairly snubbed and that Bruno Mars, the safe choice, won just about everything. Which is pretty fair, there's a legitimate problem with the Grammys. That can't be understated. But the music does have an even bigger problem in that the truly interesting and groundbreaking projects don't get their time in the limelight.

The movie industry have the Oscars. Despite the Oscar's well documented problems, the Best Picture nominations constantly serve as a must watch list in the month's before the ceremony. Whereas, the Grammy's Album of the Year list is just about as predictable and safe as the eventual winner. Which, this year's issues aside, points towards the bigger problem: none of this is surprising.

The Monthly Mix for February 2018 is pretty surprising though. Not only because it's one of the longest playlists yet, but also in the return of Parquet Courts, Father John Misty, Courtney Barnett, MF Doom and more.

There's Kali Uchis, Jay Som, James Blake, Tune-Yards, Superorganism, David Byrne, Young Fathers, Unknown Mortal Orchestra and a bunch more. All in one bumper monthly playlist.

October 2017.title: October 2017
October 2017.description:
So everything is political now and that's probably not what you signed up to this new music newsletter for. However, the past month has seen a wave of sexual harassment allegations, some of which were made against musicians that I've featured on Monthly Mix. In most cases artists have put out hollow statements in defense of their actions and been dropped by their labels.

I won't waste your time by listing them here – most have been well publicised and aren't that difficult to find if you're interested – but I'm also conscious of not wasting your, and other listeners, time too. So I've removed them from old playlists. I highly value the archive that is being added to month on month and the presence of these artists were tainting them.

I can't believe that in 2017 we're still having to talk about this stuff. But here we are...

Anyway, some new music came out again this month. So here's the Monthly Mix for October 2017

LCD Soundsystem returned, Animal Collective are back to their best and Beach Fossils continue to impress with their new sound. That's only a seventh of this playlist too!
